MFA

base=read.csv("D:/base.csv",sep=',',header=T)

First we comfirme that there is no missing value in the data.

all(!is.na(base))
## [1] TRUE

And create work data commune whith the zipcode as row names

commune=data.frame(base[,-1],row.names = base$depcom)

Then we model the first 12 variables as qualitative, and the last 14 are quantitative.

for (i in 1:12)
{commune[,i]=as.factor(commune[,i])}

Start multiplivative factor analys

library(FactoMineR)
res.mfa <- MFA(commune, 
               group = c(12,14), 
               type = c("n", "s"), 
               #group by quantitative and qualitative 
               graph = FALSE)

Eigenvalues / The proportion of variances retained by the different dimensions (axes) show as follow:

library("factoextra")
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
eig.val <- get_eigenvalue(res.mfa)
head(eig.val)

#To plot the groups of variables

fviz_mfa_var(res.mfa, "group")

Group1(qualitative) Contributions to dimension 1

fviz_contrib(res.mfa, choice = "quali.var", axes = 1, top = 20,
             palette = "jco")

Group2 (quantitative) Contributions to dimension 1

fviz_contrib(res.mfa, choice = "quanti.var", axes = 1, top = 20,
             palette = "jco")

To create a bar plot of qualitative variables cos2 and axe 1:

fviz_cos2(res.mfa, choice = "quali.var", axes = 1)

To create a bar plot of quantitative variables cos2 and axe 1:

fviz_cos2(res.mfa, choice = "quanti.var", axes = 1)
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

Correlation between qualitative variables and dimensions.

fviz_mfa_var(res.mfa, "quali.var", palette = "jco", 
             col.var.sup = "violet", repel = TRUE)

# Correlation between quantitative variables and dimensions.

fviz_mfa_var(res.mfa, "quanti.var", palette = "jco", 
             col.var.sup = "violet", repel = TRUE)

Color by Contribution values: qualitative on the factor map

fviz_mfa_var(res.mfa, "quali.var", col.var = "contrib", 
             gradient.cols = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"), 
             col.var.sup = "violet", repel = TRUE,
             geom = c("point", "text"))

Color by Contribution values: quantitative on the factor map

fviz_mfa_var(res.mfa, "quanti.var", col.var = "contrib", 
             gradient.cols = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"), 
             col.var.sup = "violet", repel = TRUE,
             geom = c("point", "text"))
